f amino acids","Primary active transport of glucose","Facilitated diffusion through water channels","Passive diffusion through tight junctions","Active transport of sodium via sodium-potassium ATPase"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport of sodium via sodium-potassium ATPase\u003C/strong\u003E on the basolateral membrane is essential for establishing the electrochemical gradient that drives transcellular reabsorption. This primary active transport process uses ATP to pump sodium out of the cell into the blood while bringing potassium into the cell.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sodium gradient established by the sodium-potassium ATPase provides the driving force for secondary active transport of many other substances across the apical membrane into the cell.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive diffusion through tight junctions\u003C/strong\u003E describes paracellular transport, not transcellular reabsorption. \u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitated diffusion through water channels\u003C/strong\u003E is a separate process that occurs via aquaporins. \u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary active transport of glucose\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur as glucose transport is secondary active, dependent on the sodium gradient. \u003Cstrong\u003EDirect transport of amino acids\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs via secondary active transport mechanisms dependent on sodium gradients. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Transcellular reabsorption in the kidney requires active transport of sodium across the basolateral membrane via sodium-potassium ATPase.","The sodium gradient created by the sodium-potassium ATPase drives secondary active transport of other substances.","Transcellular transport involves movement across both apical and basolateral cell membranes."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 28; pg. 344."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96180"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18563"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96180"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T11:42:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T11:42:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11295"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114180"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","link